          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# Hey Priya \uD83D\uDC4B\n\nFirst — a genuine acknowledgment here. You're asking exactly the right questions. Connecting your energy levels to your fueling and thinking proactively about what might be happening in your body? That's a smart, experienced runner thinking like a coach. The fact that you're paying attention to these signals matters.\n\nThat said, I want to be honest with you about where my lane ends and someone else's begins — because you deserve accurate guidance, not a coach improvising outside their expertise.\n\n---\n\n## On the light-headedness — this one needs a proper look\n\nLight-headedness after runs is something I genuinely want you to take seriously. It *can* be related to nutrition or hydration, but it can also point to things like low iron, low ferritin, blood pressure changes, or other factors that need a blood panel to sort out — not a guess from me.\n\n**I'd really encourage you to see your GP or a sports medicine doctor before we go further on the nutrition side.** Ask them specifically about ferritin and iron levels (not just haemoglobin — ferritin can be depleted even when standard iron looks \"fine,\" and it matters a lot for endurance athletes). Please don't start iron supplementation without that bloodwork — too much iron carries its own risks.\n\nOnce you have those results, we can work with them intelligently.\n\n---\n\n## On the meal plan — I have to be straight with you\n\nMeal plans are genuinely outside what I should be designing for you. A registered sports dietitian will do a far better job than I ever could — they can account for your full picture, your training load, your life, and your health history in ways I can't.\n\nWhat I *can* share is some general fueling context that's within my coaching scope — want me to walk through that?\n\n---\n\n## On keto for marathon running — let me offer some perspective here\n\nBefore you go down that road, it might help to know what the research actually shows, and then you can decide what feels right for you.\n\n**Here's the honest picture:**\n\nFat adaptation is real, and keto does increase the body's capacity to burn fat. But marathon racing — especially at your target pace of **4:32/km** — is a high-intensity effort that relies heavily on carbohydrate as fuel. Your muscles simply *can't* process fat fast enough at that intensity to sustain that pace.\n\nThe studies on keto and endurance athletes (including a well-known one by Burke et al.) have generally shown that fat adaptation **impairs carbohydrate oxidation** — meaning your body becomes less efficient at using the fuel you actually need most on race day. Elite marathon training and racing is almost universally carbohydrate-supported, not fat-fueled.\n\nWhat often helps more for long-run energy is simpler: **are you fueling *during* your long runs?** Many runners under-fuel mid-run and then blame their diet or metabolism. For runs over 75–90 minutes, taking on carbohydrates during the run (every 30–45 minutes) can make a dramatic difference in how the back half of a long run feels.\n\n---\n\n## What I'm curious about\n\nWhat does your fueling look like *during* your long runs right now — are you taking anything in, and if so, what and when? That might be the quickest lever we have while the medical side gets sorted."
        }
      ],
